06613nam a22009255i 9789048552313DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485523137 a10.1515/97890485523132doi  a(DE-B1597)634044  a(OCoLC)1346080292  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aLIT0000002bisacsh00aScreening the Gothic in Australia and New Zealand :bContemporary Antipodean Film and Television /ced. by Kate Cantrell, Jessica Gildersleeve. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHorror and Gothic Media Cultures ;v200tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction : Please Check the Signal: Screening the Gothic in the Upside Down -- tPart I Gothic Places -- t1. Unsettled Waters: The Postcolonial Gothic of Tidelands -- t2. ‘When I Died, I Saw the Whole World’ : Uncanny Space and the Māori Gothic in the Aftermath Narratives of Waru and Māui’s Hook -- t3. The Kettering Incident: From Tasmanian Gothic to Antarctic Gothic -- t4. ‘Going Home is One Thing This Lot of Blockheads Can’t Do’ : Unhomely Renovations on The Block -- tPart II Gothic Genres -- t5. Glocalizing the Gothic in Twenty-First Century Australian Horror -- t6. Terra Somnambulism : Sleepwalking, Nightdreams, and Nocturnal Wanderings in the Televisual Australian Gothic -- t7. Gothic Explorations of Landscapes, Spaces, and Bodies in Jane Campion’s Top of the Lake and Top of the Lake: China Girl -- t8. At the End of the World : Animals, Extinction, and Death in Australian Twenty-First-Century Ecogothic Cinema -- tPart III Gothic Monsters -- t9. Dead, and Into the World : Localness, Culture, and Domesticity in New Zealand’s What We Do in the Shadows -- t10. Mapping Settler Gothic : Noir and the Shameful Histories of the Pākehā Middle Class in The Bad Seed -- t11. Monstrous Victims : Women, Trauma, and Gothic Violence in Jennifer Kent’s The Babadook and The Nightingale -- t12. From ‘Fixer’ to ‘Freak’: Disabling the Ambitious (Mad)Woman in Wentworth -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe persistent popularity of the detective narrative, new obsessions with psychological and supernatural disturbances, as well as the resurgence of older narratives of mystery or the Gothic all constitute a vast proportion of contemporary film and television productions. New ways of watching film and television have also seen a reinvigoration of this ‘most domestic of media’. But what does this ‘domesticity’ of genre and media look like ‘Down Under’ in the twenty.first century? This collection traces representations of the Gothic on both the small and large screens in Australia and New Zealand in the twenty.first century. It attends to the development and mutation of the Gothic in these post. or neo.colonial contexts, concentrating on the generic innovations of this temporal and geographical focus.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aContemporary horror and ghost stories. 4aFilm Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aGothic. 4aMedia Studies. 4aPsychology. 4aRadio and Television. 4aSocial, group or collective psychology. 4aTelevision production: technical and background skills. 4aTransnational and Global Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aGothic, Australia, New Zealand, film, television.1 aBalanzategui, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCantrell, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCantrell, Kate, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDoolan, Emma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGildersle